Cmt on The Precious Treasury of the Way of Abiding, #46


Dawai: Dzogchen is exceptional because with the pointing-out instructions, which ideally should come first, teachers---Lamas, Rinpoches, Geshes, Khenpos, whoever---they will typically evaluate a practitioner and say, "Oh, you are not ready for the pointing-out," or, "You are ready for the pointing-out." So then they will prescribe, essentially, some practices: "You are stealing too much. You are lying too much. Go take some vows, right, to get your mind right." So you stop feeling like a jerk all the time, and then maybe you will see awareness.

Then other practices, you know: "You need to stare at an apple for two hours to get your mind stable." You know, do some object meditation. Stay with your breath for 10 minutes a day, you know, whatever it is. You know, some people could even start at 10 breaths; just staying with your breath for 10 times. It is very, very powerful. If you are brand new to stability practices or meditation, even five breaths---just staying with five breaths---can begin to stabilize the mind.

Of course, I always say boycott---wait, boycott? Yeah, boycott media. If you really want to get your mind right, I guess that is a boycott because your viewership is really, these days, valuable. Whether you subscribe, whether you view, your attention is very, very valuable. So you can boycott with your attention. (Holy crap, that just kind of sprung out of nowhere) And so all types of practices are prescribed so that you can get to the point, including yoga asanas and intense breath and inner heat practices to clear out karma so that you can see this:

[Dawai looking at screen] Pure presence of the mind.

Let's do an example. Let's say you could point somebody to the pure presence of mind outside of thoughts---the basis for all experience---just by saying, "Hey," and that pure presence. All right, now, [Sangha's name], try it with me. Try that same method. Point me to it.

"Hey."

[Dawai showing being distraction] "Hey, what's up? Yeah, what's up, dude?"

You see how I'm not even looking at you? I'm not even---so it's impossible, isn't it? You have to have some stability of the mind so that somebody can even say, [snapping fingers] "Hey."

So thus we have all these provisional practices. And by the way, I didn't mean to ignore you. "Hey." But that's what it feels like. How'd that feel, [Sangha's name]? How's it feel to be in my shoes for a second? Well, I don't have shoes, [laughing] but...

Sangha: My first pointing-out went so poorly. [laughing]

Dawai: Well, thankfully you were preaching to the choir. [laughing]

That makes sense, right, everybody? Why are we out of all these provisions? And then once somebody sees this and they see, "Wow, my body, my speech, my mind has been an expression within, just like reflections on a mirror. I have never not been mind: pure luminosity." And the very thing that recognizes that, like water into water, like the child meeting the mother, is then free. Then the yogis go smoke and drink and do all this stuff if they want to. Some are very opposite of that: heterodox, orthodox, left-hand path, right-hand path, Madhyamaka---the middle path. Right? You can probably find yourself somewhere. This is definitely a more middle to right-hand path. Not a lot of dark practices happening in here. [laughing]

So that being said, I feel we read this text a lot, but we don't talk about the fact that it's completely based on this awareness. And that's how Dzogchen starts. You see this... and everybody has seen it, but they haven't acknowledged it. So just a few minutes ago, or a minute ago, I was playing with my mala while [name] was talking to me. I know that because there was a pure presence of mind there holding that experience.  Well just like that, every sentient being, they know, "Oh, I just got out of my car." They know that because awareness is there, but they don't acknowledge awareness as: you can actually orientate yourself into this part of your mind. And that's the way of abiding, okay?

Because this awareness holds every concept. People have 20,000 to 40,000 thoughts a day, whatever. People know about 10,000 to 20,000 words. That's all being held by the same awareness. You have a spectrum of feelings from sadness to joy; none of those escapes awareness, just like my hand cannot get out of space. You want to try again? Try to get your hand out of space. Move it over here. Is that out of space? [Sangha's name] did you just hide your hand? That's cheating. [laughing] All right, [name] got it; she's the only one that I'll give credit to.

But this is really---we think, "Oh, I wasn't in awareness." How many times have we heard that in these gatherings? "I wasn't in awareness." To me, every time I hear that, it's like, "I wasn't in space." What's perhaps more accurate is that you are orientated into awareness. And that's a little bit getting pedantic with semantics, but I think it's worthwhile. "Oh, Dawai, I wasn't orientated into awareness." At least acknowledge that it was there. So that's why we have Ineffability, the first Great Samaya of this book, because it holds all these concepts and everything.

Everything.  So we have Oneness, which is the Fourth Great Samaya. And it has to be Purely Present, which is the Third Great Samaya, and Vastly Spacious, which is the Second Great Samaya. It has to be like that in order to remember that I was just playing with my mala, talking to [Sangha's name], If awareness closed up here, then I wouldn't be able to include the mala part.  [laughing] Or just be focused on my robe.

[Audio tech interruption omitted]

Those are the Four Great Samayas. If at any time my mind wasn't open, I wouldn't have been able to include that I was messing with this mala. I needed to include all of it: the sound, the doing of it, the thinking of it, what [name] was saying to me, the appearance. All of it was there naturally in awareness. So you have Oneness, Presence, Ineffability, and Openness all together. Right? And that's what this text is about, everybody---that your mind has these four great qualities. And of course, this is translated by Chökyi Nyima (Richard Barron), and it's a text by Longchenpa, written, published in the 1300s.

And we'll start with the root verses of The Way of Abiding. So it has these root verses and then his commentary on it. It says:

>The source of everything is revealed within the larger scope of awareness:

>>In awareness, a supreme evenness free of extremes, phenomena---the world of appearances and possibilities, whether of samsara or nirvana---arise ceaselessly. Even as they arise, neither mind nor phenomena can be characterized as "things." They are embraced within openness, the nature of phenomena.

Dawai: And you see, everybody, that's why phenomena can liberate. That's why your mind can liberate. Because this cognizant aspect, what we're calling awareness, is present, always there.

And you can validate that for yourself. If awareness is always there while I'm thinking, maybe I can be in awareness instead of the thinking. If awareness is there while I'm getting nervous while I'm driving, maybe I can be in awareness instead of in the nervousness. If awareness is there while I'm sick and I have a fever, maybe I can be in awareness instead of located into that sickness with nowhere to go. That sucks. Okay, so the auto-commentary goes on to say:

>All phenomena of the world of appearances and possibilities, whether of samsara or nirvana, arise within awareness, manifest within awareness, and are freed within awareness, so they are embraced within awareness. Phenomena and awareness, moreover; are embraced within openness, the nature of phenomena beyond characterization or description, and so are totally pure by nature.

Dawai:  Yeah everybody, and it's very, very tricky to see, just like when you're dreaming, holy crap, this body is actually luminous cognition---active consciousness. But it's possible. I'm telling you, it's possible. You don't need to shortchange Dzogchen or enlightenment. You can have it just the way it's described as long as you're approaching it truly. This body reveals itself to be luminosity. That's all it's ever been. But we get located in the physicality of the reifications, and then it seems like there's bhavana, the becoming and the ceasing. It seems like that. But if you can manage, if you want to follow these teachings, you will see the whole mind, the whole mirror, not just the reflections.

>The All-Creating Monarch states:

Dawai: By the way, that's Sarva Dharma Bodhicitta Mahasandhi Kulayaraja. I'm pretty sure I got that. I love the fact that it has bodhicitta in the All-Creating Monarch. The English translation, "The All-Creating Monarch," kind of shortchanges it. That's really the only Kulayaraja part. So anyway, it's one of our favorite texts, of course---35 chapters of pure goodness.

[p. 159]

And it says:

>>Therefore, the entire universe of appearances and possibilities
is such that everything abides within the realm of space.
Buddhas, ordinary beings, and the universe all abide
in the same way, given the vast domain of the supreme expanse of awakened mind In the totally pure nature of phenomena, everything is nondual, free of all exaggeration or denigration

>The meaning of the holy positive vajra theme is summarized:

>>The seal of awakened mind, beyond which no one goes,
is timelessly applied through supreme and wholly positive spaciousness, is embraced by the enlightened intent of the guru, protector of beings and spiritual master, and is itself sealed as the ever-awakened state, the vajra heart essence. This definitive meaning of the supreme secret is not within the reach of anyone who is not of the highest intelligence and good fortune. The theme of the vajra pinnacle is that there is no transition or change. Although this vast expanse of enlightened intent---utterly lucid, self-knowing awareness---is within oneself, it is difficult to always realize this. It is seen through the grace of the guru, glorious protector and spiritual master. It is termed "all phenomena embraced within uninterrupted openness."

And then Longchenpa says:

>Since there is no phenomenon that is not included within awakened mind––that is, awareness––we say that "no one goes beyond the embrace of mind." Indeed, The All-Creating Monarch states:

>>There is no phenomenon other than what is included
within mind.

Longchenpa says:

>No phenomenon of samsara or nirvana wavers from the expanse of Samantabhadra, [the all-good] the nature of phenomena.

Dawai: Now, what I really like about the above passage is that it tells you that lucidity is synonymous with awareness. So if you scroll back up a little bit to the root verses:

"utterly lucid," and then a comma,self-knowing awareness. So those two mean the same thing. So here we have a whole new way of looking at the word "lucid" and what that points to. It's not a sleepy lucidity that we're referencing here, but the depth is the same. So when you do lucid dreaming, you create a tree from the depth of your mind rather than the coarse linguistic narratives. Not to say that the coarse linguistic narrative can't be creative in a dream, it can, but dreams start to initiate in the hypnagogic state through a deep lucidity. It's at a deeper level than that coarse thinking, narrating mind.

And so that's the lucidity that now many of you, particularly those who have been introduced to Tögal, you're able to include all the elements into your awareness, and that lucidity is then sort of harmonized as the five lights.

So it's very, very strange, of course, to think, "Well, how can my wisdom of discernment correlate with fire?" Or how can it be the counterpart of desire? And how does earth and solidity factor into this? How does that associate with my mind? So these are things that become revealed, particularly when we go to sleep; we create solidity, we create fire, we can---and we can even create an entire experience of getting burned by that fire. That's how powerful our mind is, and how multi-dimensional it is. It creates the fire, and then it burns our own butt with the fire. And we're divided into a subdivision of cognition, so we're in the suburbs here. [laughing] It's a very beautiful root verse there.

Reading chat: So we have a question.  Asking for a friend: what is the difference between presence and spacing out?

Dawai: Spacing out is when you're going into a state of consciousness. Pure presence holds the spacing out. So you can space out as pure presence, actually. So technically, there's no difference, spacing out is pure presence. But if you want to speak in relative terms---like if you're doing a 10-minute session, or you're trying to familiarize with the view---then spacing out means you're kind of like, "Oh, I wonder what I'm going to do tomorrow." You're kind of zoning out, and staying present would be here, no thoughts are captivating you so it's like a thief entering an empty house. Okay?

Reading chat: "So equanimity versus thoughts?"

Dawai: Yeah, evenness, equanimity, fourth-time abiding. Yeah, I think you're on to it.

Reading root verse:

>Overwhelming the Six Modes of Consciousness with Splendor states:

>>Within the wholly positive context itself, free of anything needing to be done, samsara is wholly positive, nirvana is positive ...

So that's a reference to... anybody remember the six modes of consciousness? I'll give you a cookie. I could use different terminology, but we've got to get good at this decoding stuff if we're going to dig into Dharma texts. So we have seeing, hearing, smelling, tasting, tactile sensations. And then the sixth one is thoughts and emotions. So thinking, feeling, mind. Remember, Manas-vijnana in Sanskrit. Well, it looks like I caught you all slipping a little bit. So now you know, whatever.

Responding to chat: And yes, they're related to the ayatanas. Except the ayatanas are subdivided even more into the three spheres that we were discussing earlier. And the spheres of the sense-spheres are the ayatanas. Very good.

Now we're always going to stay rooted in the sutras here, everybody. Sutras and meditation is the foundation of my whole approach. I'm gonna be honest with you. So right there, just the title of this scripture gives you a lot. Anybody want to take a guess? How would you overwhelm these six modes of consciousness with splendor? Aren't we in the thinking? Aren't we in the seeing and the feeling and hearing? How can we overwhelm those?

Reading chat: "By chilling out the heart." [laughing] Thanks for that.

Dawai: Anybody want to rephrase for Dzogchen context? Yes, awareness. Exactly. Awareness is the only thing that can go outside of that boundary constraint of the ayatanas, the spheres of conception, the subject-action-object trichotomy. Nothing else can escape. Most beings are locked into those spheres and that is the issue. That is confinement. That is the real prison. A prison of the prism. A prism prison. At least you know it's not that serious, but it can feel like it's that serious. So you got it, everybody, that's how you overwhelm the six modes.

[p. 160]  And so Longchenpa says:

>The definitive meaning of Ati depends on whether blessings---which derive from the seal of the guru's sacred enlightened intent being applied---are present or not.

Dawai: Now it's going to go into how this is passed from one person to another. Throughout the past thousands of years of this Dzogchen stuff, they've been passing it sometimes only to one or two people. Because there's simply nobody whose mind can say, "Oh," you know---we say "Hey," they cannot say "Oh" and see. And remember, this path is so simple that it needs to be taught. That's why I show up every day. Because it's too easy. It's too simple. But it needs to be taught.

But this has been passed, everybody. That's the meaning of lineage: teacher to teacher to teacher. I got pointing-out instructions from several of my teachers. I probably don't need to go into it, but just so you can connect---I mean, from very powerful Anu Yoga, receiving it from Tulku Dawa and Khenchen Tsewang Gyatso, to the Dalai Lama, Avalokiteshvara Dzogchen empowerment to transmission, receiving it from him. This is being passed, the Dzogchen view is being passed, Mahamudra view, and now it's coming to you. And I'm just a kind of conduit. Conduit, that's the right word? It's just sort of passing through me, you know, to you and reminding you and activating you, just like I was activated by the grace of my guru and his love.

Khenchen Tsewang Gyatso has given his entire life to the Dharma. He has been a fully ordained monk his entire life since he was a child. Now he's older, an old age. So that, I could never even compare to that. He's just the epitome of purity on the left-hand path, or maybe Madhyamaka middle---middle way, either way.

Responding to chat: I don't study with him anymore. He teaches Shedra and he teaches the nine jhanas and things like that. But my mom still talks to him and still sees him and I'm still in communication with him. They have a new guru, the Yangsi coming in now, so Venerable Rinpoche Yangsi. But I've been really... he's with us all the time.

Dawai: So that's the main point here Longchenpa is sharing. Well, anybody here logically: how would I ever be able to show you the presence of your own mind if I have not seen it? Right? So that's the preciousness of it. There's the preciousness of it because somebody has checked out of samsara completely, they don't subscribe to the cartoon at all, not even 1%. They have to view and it's strong enough, the voltage, whatever, the BTUs, [laughing] however you want to describe that. The intensity is strong enough to where they can actually remind you and your mind is stable enough to where you see it.

And remember the four faults of Niguma---or not Niguma, remember the four faults of awareness that Niguma states? It's too simple. You show people this awareness, they're too distracted to see it. It's too simple to make sense. You think you don't deserve it. All kinds of stuff comes up that are called cognitive obscurations. And Yeshé has the four faults there in the chat. (See reference for the four faults below)

And so there has to be the two intentions. I suppose it's conventional. The teacher vows, gives their whole life to free beings, and then the being wants to be free, sincerely wants to be free. So when those two things happen, the teacher and the student come together and freedom is ensured. Along with the four conditions---but I would say four aspects---of right time, right place, right presenter, right recipient. When those things are met, realization is ensured, recognition is ensured.

And then some of these teachers are even so powerful, their intensity of their non-conceptual abiding, that even the bugs are benefiting. The cats and the dogs, every encounter, whether it appears good or bad, is like a reminder. Maybe that's why it was popular to smack the yogis upside the head to give them a pointing out, or Patrul Rinpoche got dragged by his hair, got hit by a shoe, all kinds of stuff. Nowadays, his teacher would be in prison. So it's a little bit different. [laughing]

So let's just continue a little bit here because it's on a point, an important point. There aren't many yogis out there that are passing this anymore. And then Vajrayana, the guru situation is out of hand. I can't even honestly ask people to trust. Why would you trust anybody, any guru? Why? It's scary. It takes time. Get to know your teachers. If the teacher is displaying realization, then okay. And you see that, you verify that. But it's okay to verify the teachers, to get to know them, to take your time, to challenge them, to look them up, whatever. It's fine, in my opinion. In fact, when it comes to teachers, getting to know them, Patrul Rinpoche says, could take even many years. So..

[p. 160-161]

>The Heart Essence of Secrets states:

>>The elusive and hidden meaning that is elicited
abides in the teacher---vajra mind.

Remember, the ultimate teacher is awareness, isn't it? Because if the teacher reminds me of awareness, then me and the teacher---for example, Khenchen---me and him are now meeting at that. So that's what they call, my mind has become one with the teacher. That's what they mean by Guru Yoga. That's the whole purpose of Guru Yoga, is that you're mingling your mind with awareness. So your awareness is becoming that awareness, one and the same. But you still have your own mind, okay? But that mind of yours is now the enlightened mind, no difference from the enlightened mind of your teacher. So it says:

> As this shows, that which is ultimately meaningful is the "enlightened intent of the vajra pinnacle." This itself is not within the reach of anyone who is not of the highest intelligence.

And we could say acumen, we could say, but typically, you know, modern people are very, very sharp and so it's talking about pretty much modern people, in my opinion.

>The All-Creating Monarch states:

>>Countless eons ago, those who had faith in me, all-creating enlightenment---those with the suitable karma and good fortune,  utterly immersed in genuine being---had no view to cultivate in meditation, no samaya to uphold,no enlightened activity involving effort, no paths to traverse, no levels of realization on which to train, no causality, no twofold division into ultimate and relative, nothing to cultivate in meditation or achieve, no motivation to be aroused, and no antidotes. So that they might perceive the nature of all creating mind, I revealed it for just this purpose.

Here you have the Kunjed Gyalpo defining itself. It said, "countless eons ago, those who had faith in me, all-creating enlightenment." That tells you everything. When the Kunjed Gyalpo says, "I am the creator of all animate and inanimate," it's talking about your all-creating enlightenment. It's very creative and powerful. But when you start to create things, destructive and things like that, you start to put yourself in check. Just like something is breathing your lungs right now, something grew your brain, something maintained your brain. Something is maintaining until you're mature enough to come into your creativity. It's going to regulate that, just like the baby bird is regulated by the eggshells until it's ready.

Reading chat: "Is awareness Buddha-nature?"

Dawai: Yes. In here, we typically call the essence emptiness, Dharmakaya. The nature is awareness, Sambhogakaya, Buddha-nature, Svabhavikakaya, Rangjung. And so if you were all made out of water right now, which you kind of are, and I said---well, let's just stick with the regular examples. Everything that's water has the nature of wetness, whether you're talking about a lake, a cup of water, spit, it all has the nature of wetness. All fire has the nature of heat. So you have, whether it's a lighter, whether it's a campfire, a stove fire, it all has the nature of heat. Just like that, all reality, all experiences have the nature of awareness. This cognitive aspect, which is how we can reorientate into the pure aspect and allow for self-liberation, that Rangdrol, even Rangjung. Very good.

>Moreover, the ultimate meaning of utterly lucid enlightened intent---...

Dawai: And remember enlightened beingness can squeeze in there. Enlightened intent is a reference to the second of the Eightfold Path, so it comes after right view, and so that way, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effortlessness, right mindfulness, and right concentration. So you're able to hold anything within awareness as long as you want. All that comes from awareness, right view. That's why right view is in the beginning. There are many provisional explanations of right view, but this is the truest, in my opinion, the highest implementation of the Eightfold Path.

And that's why we don't really have to worry about our speech, our actions. Our intelligence can finally flourish within spaciousness. You don't need to micromanage it. That's why I don't understand intellectualism. People who say, "No, we're going to make a life in intellectualism. We're going to stick to our intellectualism. It's the only thing that we know is right, and it's the only thing we can depend on." I don't get it. Maybe they need a brain injury like me. [laughing] Just kidding. No brain injuries.

So this is really beautiful, you know. The text cont':

>...utterly lucid enlightened intent---beyond description or imagination and perceived through the
grace of the guru---is openness, for it goes beyond the limitation of existence or nonexistence. The All-Creating Monarch states:

>>Extremely immediate timeless awareness, utterly unimaginable, is like a precious gem bestowed by all spiritual mentors.

Dawai: Aah yes–so thankful. And you know, you may have Yidams who are Rinpoche, Tara, the nirmanakaya teachers like Khenchen, Dalai Lama. I know for some of you, you have Lamas, just regular no-name Lamas who have too many dogs. You have them as your teacher. But it's like, thank you, my friend, thanks for sharing this with me. Right? Like with my teachers, I'm just like, thank you so much. I won't abuse this gift.

So that's kind of my take on it, everybody. And thank you for joining today with this text exploration of The Way of Abiding.

We are hitting this year strong right now with the Dharma. And I feel like the basis is becoming very powerful in this group. You practitioners that are just here, just in keeping it real. I really appreciate you so much for that.

